                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I read here often, though I'm not much one for posting, but I thought I'd share a perspective. I read a lot, as I tend to obsessively study information on the game; I'm a student of it, and play frequently.
<br />

<br />
I play a lot of toons; I like to experience EQ from all sides. In some people's books, that disqualifies me from commenting. Other people recognize that skill comes from experience and is somewhat inherent, and that there are plenty one-toon enchanters who can't hold a candle skillwise. I only 2box; SK/enc/dru on one account, necro/bard/shaman on secondary, and yes, I've considered moving the druid many times. <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" /> So, for what it's worth: 
<br />

<br />
My first toon was a druid, then I made my enchanter, and she was my first 'love', I suppose you could say, precisely because of the exhilarating thrill of crowd control. That was what drew me, and I'm sure many others to the class. Sebilis sort of represents the heyday of enchanterhood. As I leveled, however, my guild at the time was very short on enchanters. There was myself, and another who worked a lot and was thus unavailable. Most of the time, I spent buffing. This was early PoP, which was a rather large jump in mob dps, and instead of derailing trains, I was dying because we pulled an extra giant in BoT that I either couldn't mez, or couldn't live through beating on me for a round if mez was resisted. Single pulls became the norm, and on raids, since I was the only enchanter, I was somewhat treated as a glass doll. My guildies trusted my capabilities, but they'd rather single pull and keep me alive for rebuffing people and mezzing only in emergencies. This sort of killed my enthusiasm for her, and later, my SK became my 'main' for all intents and purposes. 
<br />

<br />
My raiding body is in Qvic currently; we're the only ones on E'ci who are there (in fact, I'm the only SK, heh). That involves a lot of raiding, but I primarily xp with my enchanter, except for currently as I push to 70 on my SK first.
<br />

<br />
What I find interesting is the experiences people have in groups and raids. For example, on our raids, enchanters pull. They're kept very active in all zones but the latter phases of Time, really. They're in constant motion, pulling, mezzing, keeping mobs in camp, calling unmezzables for us to tank. Our bards are our china dolls that we keep in camp, alive, and don't risk very much; I've raided frequently with all of my toons, and bard is by far the most inactive/boring/bottable class, compared to the activity in xp groups. I like SK because I'm active in both groups and raids; I'm moving, hitting buttons, doing something. One day, I realized, that's what has drawn me to my various classes. I like controllers. Offtanking, pulling, mezzing, slowing, singing. I need to be doing something, or I lose interest and drift off. 
<br />

<br />
I find this common with a lot of enchanters who have complaints. Call it a high-stimulus personality or something, but just as you find a lot of healers who are content to hit one button over and over again every 20 seconds and do nothing else..well, I'm sure you can equate the converse of that to the gripes of many enchanters.
<br />

<br />
Perhaps it's the groups I'm in, both as her and as other toons, but when we have an enchanter, to us it represents the ability to do more, pull faster, keep more in camp. Without an enchanter, we single things. Enchanters let us push the envelope. We took a group into Ferubi today for cleric epic pages, and it was our ability to continually keep moving and maintaining mobs in camp that enabled us to succeed. Enchanters mean we can be aggressive instead of passive; this is true in LDoN, WoS, Yxtta, Ferubi, whatever. Sure, you need an on-the-ball healer at times, and sometimes, that mez resist one-rounds our enchanter, but..it's a dichotomy change that I don't feel with other classes, except bard, whose effectiveness diminishes out of camp while enchanter's does not. Mez is powerful. Too many people say, well, my group only pulls singles. It's trite and clich to say "well, you're not in the right groups", because hey, you very well could be in a wonderful group. There are some areas that we only pull singles in, sure. That's going to happen. However, the people I know value enchanters for their ability to help us push the envelope.
<br />

<br />
That being said, I think it's ridiculous we have such paltry AE controls nowadays, and survivability in some zones on mez resists is ridiculous; a mez resist shouldn't wipe a party, as that puts too much emphasis on luck, not skill. Heads, we survive, tails, the enchanter and cleric die in &lt; 5 seconds? That's ridiculous. I'm also not happy with the charm changes in OOW, because charm's a large part of my repertoire, and I think the high risk/low reward is plain silly. Yes, we have issues. But I dont see where we're dying off or being eliminated. Are we necessary? No. Desirable? Yes. A lot of classes have issues. That's an unfortunate state of the game.
<br />

<br />
We are always at our weakest in the early stage of an expansion. OOW, at least, is 'easier' than GoD, in that we still maintain a large portion of our abilities in xp'able zones. 
<br />

<br />
A lot approach it from the perspective of: All pulls used to be X+1, and now they're X, and that bores me because I want something to do, crowd control is dead. 
<br />

<br />
The role has evolved. Now, what I perceive is: Groups without enchanters are X-1, and groups with enchanters can pull X, and that excites me because it keeps us all more involves and active and lets us accomplish more, because we have the ability to control crowds and keep ourselves moving forward instead of being stagnant.I don't know about you, but I'd rather be at X than X-1. If you're with familiar people, your X is X+1, X+2, whatever. If we lack an enchanter, we grumble about it. 
<br />

<br />
You can't *require* crowd control. If you assume a baseline of the majority of pulls being singlable, and work forward, you'll get what I'm used to. Crowd control is active now. It's not sit-in-camp, it's pre-targeting, sniping in incoming, working with your tank and puller, crawling instead of sitting, whatever.
<br />

<br />
Then, work from there. 
<br />

<br />
So what I don't grasp--and this seems to be the inherent conflict--is that some people complain that they don't do anything, but every day, I play or welcome an enchanter into my group or raid, and see them not only active, but enabling the entire group to do more. The enchanter is an active, contributing part of our groups. Attention is necessary and desired.
<br />

<br />
Charm needs fixing. Our tools to control more effective need work. Our survivability issues (depending on zone and gear) are primarily rooted in our inability to reliably ditch aggro (half the time, I think we should have FM, half the time, I think it'd be too powerful..the truth probably is somewhere in between), and Doppleganger's poor in comparison but at least it's a step. But dead? Un-fun? I don't see that at all, and it saddens me that some people's experiences are that they sit in camp and do nothing. The unfortunate thing is that I don't know what can be done to change the perception of random pickup group strangers that 1-in-camp is the best way to spend one's time.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
