                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">And the ones that did, never charmed for DPS untill Planes of Power came out. 
<br />

<br />
Oh waaa, enchanters are being pushed back to their original purpose in game. A support class that has nifty abilities. We're not going to be neglected to the point of being clarity whores. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I think that is a misstatement of the class.  Let's see - yes, I know what hell levels are, and charm came into it's own when they un-nerfed pet exp (summoned and charmed) in early Luclin.  Luclin was also the expansion that first really rewarded charm.  That was when I switched over to mainly charming for solo exp, both druid and enchanter; and yes, I had soloed my (then) enchanter without.
<br />

<br />
Back in the day, the primary role of an enchanter was crowd control.  Not buffing.  The buffs and slow were great, but you took an enchanter because you couldn't run an exp group without CC; lull pulling didn't work until early PoP.  That was the basis of the trinity - tank, healer and crowd control - NOT slower.  Exp groups were all in dungeons, and even DL/OT groups wanted CC.
<br />

<br />
Two factors have destroyed the crowd control role: lull pulling, and the bizarre choice to scale mobs faster than players.  A caster is no longer suitable for CC because of the second factor, and not required because of the first, and because of the universal choice to design zones as open fields, along the LOIO model.
<br />

<br />
That left us with buffs and charm; which I think must be where you came into the class, although I suppose it is just possible for someone to start in Velious and ignore charm for the 6+ months before PoP where it was strong.  But you are right in that the mob scaling in PoP meant that charmed pets made a much bigger difference to groups than ever before.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
